initial_story: in recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (cnns) have beenapplied for image recognition successfully. quantum convolutional neuralnetworks (qcnns) are proposed as a novel generalization to cnns by usingquantum mechanisms. the quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient trainingprocess in qcnns by reducing the size of input from $n$ to $log_2n$. this paperimplements and compares both cnns and qcnns by testing losses and predictionaccuracy on three commonly used datasets. the datasets include the mnisthand-written digits, fashion mnist and cat/dog face images. additionally, dataaugmentation (da), a technique commonly used in cnns to improve the performanceof classification by generating similar images based on original inputs, isalso implemented in qcnns. surprisingly, the results showed that dataaugmentation didn't improve qcnns performance. the reasons and logic behindthis result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of quantummachine learning theory.
stories: In recent years, natural language processing (NLP) models have been applied for sentiment analysis with remarkable success. Quantum recurrent neural networks (QRNNs) are proposed as a novel generalization to traditional RNNs by harnessing quantum entanglement. The quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient decoding process in QRNNs by reducing the time complexity from O(n) to O(logn). This paper investigates and compares both traditional RNNs and QRNNs by evaluating losses and prediction accuracy on three commonly used text datasets. The datasets include the IMDB movie reviews, Stanford Sentiment Treebank and Yelp reviews. Furthermore, attention mechanism, a technique widely used in traditional NLP models to weigh the importance of input features, is also implemented in QRNNs. Interestingly, the results showed that attention mechanism didn't improve QRNNs performance. The reasons and implications behind this result are explored, aiming to deepen our understanding of quantum machine learning theory and its potential applications in NLP.
